            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kaia Flores\u2019s hands have known the feel of grease and steel since childhood. Raised in Richmond by her Filipina mother, a pragmatic nurse, and her white American father, a shipyard mechanic, her upbringing was a blend of warm family gatherings and the ordered chaos of her father\u2019s garage. She learned the Tagalog words for family and food alongside the names for every tool in a socket set. While her peers obsessed over college applications, Kaia found her future under the blue-white glare of a TIG welder in her high school\u2019s vocational arts program. The hiss of the arc and the smell of ozone felt more like home than any classroom.\n\nForegoing college, she secured an apprenticeship at a small fabrication shop in Oakland. For years, she honed her craft, her powerful, steady hands learning to bend, cut, and join metal with industrial precision. The major turning point came at 28, when she landed a job at a sought-after design-build firm in San Francisco's Dogpatch neighborhood. She moved to a small apartment in Potrero Hill, reveling in the creative energy and the view of the shipyards that reminded her of her father.\n\nNow 37, Kaia\u2019s life is a study in disciplined creation. Her day begins with a coffee on her stoop before she cycles the 2.8 miles to the workshop, a cavernous space filled with the screech of grinders and the bright flashes of welders. She fabricates high-end architectural elements\u2014custom staircases, ornate gates, and bespoke furniture\u2014for the city's elite, finding satisfaction in the flawless seams and perfect angles. Her social life is a tight-knit circle of fellow makers, artists, and tradespeople who gather at dive bars in the Mission or for weekend potlucks.\n\nDeeply connected to the city\u2019s industrial past, Kaia dreams of transitioning from fabricator to full-time artist. Her aspiration is to win a public art commission, a large-scale metal sculpture that will become a permanent part of the San Francisco landscape she now calls home. She wants to create something enduring, a testament to the beauty that can be forged from raw strength and a clear vision."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, her small hands barely wrapping around the cold steel of a torque wrench. Her father\u2019s calloused thumb guided hers. \"This is how you know it's just right, *anak*,\" he\u2019d said, using the Tagalog term of endearment as the tool gave a solid *click*. The sound echoed in the garage, a small, perfect note of certainty. It wasn't just the noise of a bolt tightening; it was the feeling of measured strength, a lesson in precision that became the foundation for everything she would ever build.\n\n2.\nAt seventeen, the world went silent behind the dark glass of her welding helmet. The hiss of the argon gas and the intense blue-white light of the arc was her sanctuary. For the first time, she laid down a perfect, unbroken bead of molten steel, a flawless \"stack of dimes.\" Lifting the mask, the smell of ozone was sharp and clean. In that glowing, seamless line, she saw her future with absolute clarity. It wasn't in a lecture hall; it was right here, forged in fire and focus.\n\n3.\nShe remembers the sickening screech of the saw veering off-line during her apprenticeship. She\u2019d ruined a costly sheet of stainless steel, and the shame was a cold knot in her stomach. Her mentor didn\u2019t yell; he just made her stare at the jagged, useless cut. The lesson wasn't about the mistake, but the unforgiving nature of the material itself. From that day on, precision became her religion, a form of profound respect for the steel and the craft.\n\n4.\nHer first morning in Potrero Hill, age 28. The air was cool and salty. With coffee in hand, she stood on her small stoop, looking east. Below, the cranes of the old shipyards stood like steel skeletons against the dawn, a direct line back to her father\u2019s world. It was a powerful, gut-level feeling of coming home to a place she\u2019d never lived. She wasn't just starting a new job; she was stepping into her own history, ready to make her mark.\n\n5.\nIt happened on a walk through SoMa a few years ago. She stopped before a massive, twisting sculpture of Cor-Ten steel, its rusted surface glowing in the afternoon sun. She had fabricated elements more complex than this, but never with such singular, defiant purpose. It wasn't a gate or a staircase; it was a statement. In that moment, the distinction between her craft and her ambition dissolved. The desire to create not just for a client, but for the city itself, became a burning need."
